================================================================================
  CIS UBUNTU 24.04 - MANUAL REMEDIATION GUIDE WITH EXPLANATIONS
  Based on Qualys Policy Compliance Scan Results
  Firewall: iptables only | OS: Ubuntu 24.04 LTS
================================================================================

WHAT IS CIS?
------------
CIS (Center for Internet Security) is a nonprofit organization that publishes
security benchmarks for operating systems. A CIS benchmark is a set of
configuration guidelines designed to protect systems from cyber threats.
When Qualys runs a CIS scan, it checks your Ubuntu system against these
benchmarks and flags any settings that do not meet the standard.

WHAT IS THIS GUIDE?
-------------------
This guide walks you through fixing every failed CIS control found in your
Qualys scan, one step at a time. Each section explains:
  - WHAT the control is
  - WHY it matters (the security risk)
  - HOW to fix it (exact commands)
  - HOW to verify the fix worked

WHO SHOULD USE THIS?
--------------------
This guide is intended for system administrators performing manual
remediation on Ubuntu 24.04 servers. No automation scripts are used —
every step is performed manually so you understand exactly what is changing.


================================================================================
CRITICAL WARNINGS - READ BEFORE STARTING
================================================================================

WARNING 1 - TAKE A SNAPSHOT
  Before making any changes, take a VM snapshot or full system backup.
  If something goes wrong, you can restore to the previous state.
  Command (on VMware/KVM host): take a snapshot from the hypervisor console.

WARNING 2 - KEEP TWO SSH SESSIONS OPEN
  When making SSH or firewall changes, always keep a second terminal window
  open and connected to the server. If your SSH config breaks or the firewall
  locks you out, you can fix it from the second session without losing access.

WARNING 3 - VALIDATE SSH BEFORE RESTARTING
  Before restarting the SSH service after any config change, always run:
      sudo sshd -t
  This checks for syntax errors. If it shows errors, fix them first.
  Never restart SSH with a broken config or you will be locked out.

WARNING 4 - FIREWALL ORDER MATTERS
  When configuring iptables, always add the ALLOW rule for SSH port 22
  BEFORE you set the default DROP policy. If you set DROP first, you
  immediately lose SSH access to the server.

WARNING 5 - TEST BEFORE PRODUCTION
  Apply all changes to a test or development server first. Verify everything
  works correctly before applying to production systems.


================================================================================
SECTION 1 - KERNEL MODULES (Disable Risky Filesystems)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  The Linux kernel can load modules on demand to support different filesystem
  types like HFS (Apple), JFFS2 (flash storage), squashfs, and others. Most
  servers never need these filesystem types.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Attackers can exploit vulnerabilities in kernel modules. If a module is
  loaded, it increases the attack surface of the system. By blacklisting
  these modules, we prevent them from ever being loaded — even if an attacker
  tries to load them. The line "install <module> /bin/true" tells the kernel
  to run /bin/true (which does nothing) instead of loading the real module.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Open or create the blacklist configuration file
      sudo nano /etc/modprobe.d/cis-blacklist.conf

  Step 2: Add the following lines exactly as shown:
      install freevxfs /bin/true
      install hfs /bin/true
      install hfsplus /bin/true
      install jffs2 /bin/true
      install squashfs /bin/true
      install udf /bin/true
      install vfat /bin/true
      install cramfs /bin/true

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 3: Unload any of these modules if they are currently loaded
      sudo modprobe -r freevxfs hfs hfsplus jffs2 squashfs udf vfat cramfs

      Note: You may see "not found" errors for modules not currently loaded.
      This is normal — it just means they were not loaded to begin with.

HOW TO VERIFY:
  Run this command — it should return NO output (empty means success):
      lsmod | grep -E 'freevxfs|hfs|jffs2|squashfs|udf|vfat|cramfs'

  If any module names appear, they are still loaded. Re-run Step 3 for
  the specific module name shown.


================================================================================
SECTION 2 - APPARMOR (Mandatory Access Control)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  AppArmor is a Linux security module that implements Mandatory Access Control
  (MAC). It restricts what programs can do by enforcing security policies
  called "profiles". Each profile defines exactly which files, capabilities,
  and network access a program is allowed to use.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Even if an attacker compromises a program (e.g. a web server), AppArmor
  prevents that program from accessing files or executing commands outside
  its defined profile. This "containment" limits the damage an attacker can
  cause. Ubuntu comes with AppArmor installed but it needs to be running
  and profiles need to be in "enforce" mode (not just "complain" mode).

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Install AppArmor and management utilities
      sudo apt install apparmor apparmor-utils -y

  Step 2: Enable AppArmor to start automatically at boot
      sudo systemctl enable apparmor

  Step 3: Start AppArmor right now (without rebooting)
      sudo systemctl start apparmor

  Step 4: Set all available profiles to enforce mode
      sudo aa-enforce /etc/apparmor.d/*
      Note: Some warnings about abstract profiles are normal and can be ignored.

HOW TO VERIFY:
      sudo apparmor_status

  Look for:
  - "apparmor module is loaded"
  - A number of profiles in "enforce" mode (should be > 0)
  - If it says "complain" mode, repeat Step 4


================================================================================
SECTION 3 - FILESYSTEM (Sticky Bit & World-Writable Files)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  World-writable means any user on the system can write to (modify or delete)
  a file or directory. The "sticky bit" on a directory is a special permission
  that means only the file's owner can delete it, even if the directory is
  world-writable. A common example is /tmp — everyone can write files there,
  but you can only delete your own files.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Without the sticky bit, any user could delete other users' files in a shared
  directory. World-writable files are dangerous because any process or user
  can modify them — including attackers or malware. Unowned files (files with
  no valid user or group) are often left behind by deleted accounts and can
  be claimed by attackers who get the same UID.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Set sticky bit on ALL world-writable directories
      df --local -P | awk '{if (NR!=1) print $6}' | \
      xargs -I '{}' find '{}' -xdev -type d -perm -0002 2>/dev/null | \
      xargs chmod a+t

      What this does: Finds every world-writable directory on all local
      filesystems and adds the sticky bit to each one.

  Step 2: Find all world-writable FILES (not directories)
      find / -xdev -type f -perm -0002 2>/dev/null

      Review the output. Files in /tmp or /dev are often expected.
      Any world-writable file outside those locations should be investigated.

  Step 3: Remove world-write permission from each unexpected file found
      sudo chmod o-w /path/to/filename

      Repeat this for each file that should not be world-writable.

  Step 4: Find files with no valid owner or group
      sudo find / -xdev \( -nouser -o -nogroup \) 2>/dev/null

  Step 5: Assign root ownership to any unowned files found
      sudo chown root:root /path/to/file

HOW TO VERIFY:
      find / -xdev -type f -perm -0002 2>/dev/null
  Should return only expected files (e.g. in /tmp, /dev).

      sudo find / -xdev \( -nouser -o -nogroup \) 2>/dev/null
  Should return no output.


