SECTION 4 - IPTABLES FIREWALL (IPv4 & IPv6)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  iptables is the standard Linux firewall tool. It controls which network
  traffic is allowed into, out of, and through the server. Rules are
  processed in order — the first matching rule wins. At the end of each
  chain is a default "policy" — either ACCEPT (allow all unmatched traffic)
  or DROP (silently discard all unmatched traffic).

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Without a firewall, any port open on the server is accessible to the entire
  internet. A default DROP policy means that only traffic explicitly allowed
  by a rule can reach the server. Everything else is silently discarded.
  We also configure ip6tables for IPv6 traffic because a server with IPv6
  enabled and no IPv6 firewall rules is effectively unprotected on IPv6.

  CIS requires:
  - Default INPUT policy: DROP (deny all inbound unless explicitly allowed)
  - Default FORWARD policy: DROP (this server does not route traffic)
  - Default OUTPUT policy: ACCEPT (allow all outbound traffic)
  - Loopback interface: always allowed
  - Established connections: allowed (so responses to our requests get through)

HOW TO FIX:

  [!] CRITICAL ORDER: Add the SSH allow rule (Step 9) BEFORE setting
      the default DROP policy (Step 10). Wrong order = locked out.

  Step 1: Install iptables and the persistence package
      sudo apt install iptables iptables-persistent -y

      The iptables-persistent package saves your rules so they survive reboots.
      During installation it may ask to save current rules — say YES.

  Step 2: Disable nftables (Ubuntu's newer firewall — we use iptables only)
      sudo systemctl disable nftables
      sudo systemctl stop nftables

  Step 3: Clear all existing IPv4 firewall rules (start fresh)
      sudo iptables -F        (flush all rules)
      sudo iptables -X        (delete all custom chains)
      sudo iptables -Z        (zero all packet/byte counters)

  Step 4: Clear all existing IPv6 firewall rules
      sudo ip6tables -F
      sudo ip6tables -X
      sudo ip6tables -Z

  Step 5: Allow all traffic on the loopback interface (127.0.0.1)
      sudo iptables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT
      sudo iptables -A OUTPUT -o lo -j ACCEPT

      The loopback interface is used for internal communication between
      processes on the same server. It must always be allowed.

  Step 6: Block any traffic claiming to be from 127.x but not on loopback
      sudo iptables -A INPUT ! -i lo -s 127.0.0.0/8 -j DROP

      This prevents IP spoofing attacks using the loopback address range.

  Step 7: Allow traffic for connections already established
      sudo iptables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT

      Without this rule, the server could send requests out but never receive
      the responses back. This allows response traffic for outgoing connections.

  Step 8: Allow DNS queries (so the server can resolve domain names)
      sudo iptables -A OUTPUT -p udp --dport 53 -j ACCEPT
      sudo iptables -A OUTPUT -p tcp --dport 53 -j ACCEPT

  Step 9: Allow SSH inbound — DO THIS BEFORE STEP 10
      sudo iptables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

      This allows you to SSH into the server. If you skip this step before
      setting DROP policy, you will immediately lose SSH access.

  Step 10: Set default policies — DROP for INPUT and FORWARD, ACCEPT for OUTPUT
      sudo iptables -P INPUT DROP
      sudo iptables -P FORWARD DROP
      sudo iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT

  Step 11: Allow IPv6 loopback traffic
      sudo ip6tables -A INPUT -i lo -j ACCEPT
      sudo ip6tables -A OUTPUT -o lo -j ACCEPT
      sudo ip6tables -A INPUT ! -i lo -s ::1 -j DROP

  Step 12: Allow IPv6 established connections
      sudo ip6tables -A INPUT -m state --state ESTABLISHED,RELATED -j ACCEPT

  Step 13: Allow IPv6 SSH
      sudo ip6tables -A INPUT -p tcp --dport 22 -j ACCEPT

  Step 14: Set IPv6 default DROP policies
      sudo ip6tables -P INPUT DROP
      sudo ip6tables -P FORWARD DROP
      sudo ip6tables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT

  Step 15: Save rules so they persist after reboot
      sudo netfilter-persistent save

HOW TO VERIFY:
      sudo iptables -L -v -n
  Look for: Chain INPUT (policy DROP), SSH ACCEPT rule, loopback ACCEPT rule

      sudo iptables -L OUTPUT -v -n
  Look for: Chain OUTPUT (policy ACCEPT)

      sudo ip6tables -L -v -n
  Look for: Same structure for IPv6

      cat /etc/iptables/rules.v4
  This file should contain your saved rules.


