SECTION 5 - SSH HARDENING
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  SSH (Secure Shell) is the primary way administrators connect to servers
  remotely. The SSH daemon (sshd) has many configuration options that control
  how connections are authenticated and what is permitted during a session.
  Default SSH settings are often too permissive for a hardened server.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  SSH is one of the most targeted services on any internet-facing server.
  Weak SSH configuration allows:
  - Root login directly (attacker only needs the root password)
  - Brute force attacks with unlimited attempts
  - Weak encryption ciphers that can be cracked
  - Session hijacking through X11 or TCP forwarding
  - Idle sessions left open indefinitely (risk if terminal is walked away from)

  We create a separate drop-in config file (/etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/99-cis.conf)
  so our changes are clearly separated from the main config and survive updates.

HOW TO FIX:

  [!] Open a second SSH session now before making changes.
  [!] Always run 'sudo sshd -t' to check config before restarting.

  Step 1: Create a CIS-specific SSH configuration file
      sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/99-cis.conf

  Step 2: Type or paste ALL of the following into the file:

      # Disable direct root login - admins must login as a normal user first
      PermitRootLogin no

      # Limit login attempts to 4 before disconnecting
      MaxAuthTries 4

      # Limit simultaneous sessions per connection
      MaxSessions 10

      # Ignore .rhosts files - old insecure authentication method
      IgnoreRhosts yes

      # Disable host-based authentication - insecure legacy method
      HostbasedAuthentication no

      # Never allow login with a blank password
      PermitEmptyPasswords no

      # Prevent users from setting environment variables via SSH
      PermitUserEnvironment no

      # Send a keepalive packet every 300 seconds (5 minutes)
      ClientAliveInterval 300

      # Disconnect after 3 missed keepalives (15 minutes total idle)
      ClientAliveCountMax 3

      # Disconnect unauthenticated connections after 60 seconds
      LoginGraceTime 60

      # Disable X11 graphical forwarding (not needed on servers)
      X11Forwarding no

      # Disable TCP port forwarding (prevents tunneling)
      AllowTcpForwarding no

      # Disable SSH agent forwarding
      AllowAgentForwarding no

      # Disable compression (can be exploited in older versions)
      Compression no

      # Log detailed information about connections
      LogLevel VERBOSE

      # Show warning banner before login
      Banner /etc/issue.net

      # Use SSH Protocol version 2 only (version 1 is broken)
      Protocol 2

      # Check file permissions and ownership before accepting login
      StrictModes yes

      # Show last login time and location on login
      PrintLastLog yes

      # Disable TCP keepalive (use ClientAlive instead)
      TCPKeepAlive no

      # Disable GSSAPI authentication (Kerberos-based, usually not needed)
      GSSAPIAuthentication no

      # Disable Kerberos authentication
      KerberosAuthentication no

      # Explicitly deny root user via SSH
      DenyUsers root

      # Only allow these strong encryption ciphers
      Ciphers aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr,aes192-ctr,aes128-ctr

      # Only allow these strong message authentication codes
      MACs hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com

      # Only allow these secure key exchange algorithms
      KexAlgorithms curve25519-sha256,curve25519-sha256@libssh.org

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 3: Validate the configuration — MUST show no errors
      sudo sshd -t

      If you see any errors, go back and fix them before proceeding.
      Common errors: duplicate settings, typos in option names.

  Step 4: Restart SSH only after Step 3 shows no errors
      sudo systemctl restart ssh

      Test your second SSH session is still working before closing the first.

  Step 5: Set correct ownership and permissions on config files
      sudo chown root:root /etc/ssh/sshd_config
      sudo chmod 600 /etc/ssh/sshd_config
      sudo chown root:root /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/99-cis.conf
      sudo chmod 600 /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/99-cis.conf

HOW TO VERIFY:
      sudo sshd -t
  Should return nothing (no errors = valid config)

      sudo grep PermitRootLogin /etc/ssh/sshd_config.d/99-cis.conf
  Should show: PermitRootLogin no

      Try logging in as root via SSH — it should be DENIED.


================================================================================
SECTION 6 - LOGIN BANNER
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  A login banner is a message displayed to users before they authenticate.
  The /etc/issue.net file is shown to SSH users before login.
  The /etc/issue file is shown on the local console before login.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  From a legal and security standpoint, a warning banner establishes that:
  - The system is for authorized users only
  - All activity is monitored
  - Unauthorized access is illegal
  This is often required for legal action against intruders and for
  compliance with regulations like PCI-DSS, HIPAA, and government standards.
  CIS requires a banner to be configured.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Open the SSH banner file
      sudo nano /etc/issue.net

  Step 2: Delete any existing content and add:
      ***************************************************************************
      NOTICE: This system is for authorized use only.
      All activity is monitored and logged.
      Unauthorized access is prohibited and will be prosecuted.
      ***************************************************************************

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 3: Copy the same banner to the local console banner file
      sudo cp /etc/issue.net /etc/issue

  Step 4: Set correct permissions on both files
      sudo chmod 644 /etc/issue.net
      sudo chmod 644 /etc/issue

HOW TO VERIFY:
  SSH to the server from another terminal — the banner text should appear
  before the password prompt.

      cat /etc/issue.net
  Should display your warning text.


