SECTION 7 - PASSWORD QUALITY (pwquality)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  pam_pwquality is a PAM (Pluggable Authentication Module) that enforces
  password complexity rules when users create or change their passwords.
  It checks that new passwords meet minimum requirements for length,
  character types, and avoids common patterns.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Weak passwords are one of the most common ways systems get compromised.
  Without complexity requirements, users may set passwords like "password123"
  or "abc123" which can be cracked in seconds. Strong password requirements:
  - Minimum length of 14 characters
  - Mix of uppercase, lowercase, numbers, and symbols
  - No dictionary words
  - No repeated or sequential characters
  make brute-force and dictionary attacks much harder.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Install the pam_pwquality module
      sudo apt install libpam-pwquality -y

  Step 2: Open the password quality configuration file
      sudo nano /etc/security/pwquality.conf

  Step 3: Add or update the following lines:
      # Minimum password length of 14 characters
      minlen = 14

      # Require at least 1 digit (-1 means at least 1 required)
      dcredit = -1

      # Require at least 1 uppercase letter
      ucredit = -1

      # Require at least 1 special character (e.g. ! @ # $)
      ocredit = -1

      # Require at least 1 lowercase letter
      lcredit = -1

      # No more than 3 consecutive identical characters (e.g. 'aaa')
      maxrepeat = 3

      # No more than 3 sequential characters (e.g. 'abc' or '123')
      maxsequence = 3

      # Check against dictionary of common words
      dictcheck = 1

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

HOW TO VERIFY:
      grep -v "^#" /etc/security/pwquality.conf | grep -v "^$"
  Should show all your configured settings.

  Try changing a password to something weak (e.g. "password") — it should
  be rejected with a message about password quality.


