SECTION 8 - PAM CONFIGURATION (Account Lockout & Password History)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  PAM (Pluggable Authentication Module) is the framework Linux uses to handle
  authentication. We configure two key security features:

  1. pam_faillock: Locks an account after a defined number of failed login
     attempts. This prevents brute force attacks.

  2. Password history (remember=): Prevents users from reusing recent
     passwords. Without this, a user could change their password and
     immediately change it back to the old one.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Without account lockout, an automated brute-force tool can try millions
  of password combinations. With lockout set to 5 attempts, an attacker
  gets very few guesses before the account is locked.
  Without password history, users rotate between 2-3 passwords, defeating
  the purpose of periodic password changes.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Backup common-auth before making any changes
      sudo cp /etc/pam.d/common-auth /etc/pam.d/common-auth.bak

  Step 2: Open the common-auth PAM file
      sudo nano /etc/pam.d/common-auth

  Step 3: Add this line at the VERY TOP of the file (before any other auth lines):
      auth required pam_faillock.so preauth silent deny=5 unlock_time=600

      What this means:
      - preauth: Check lockout status BEFORE asking for password
      - silent: Don't tell attacker why login failed
      - deny=5: Lock account after 5 failures
      - unlock_time=600: Auto-unlock after 600 seconds (10 minutes)

  Step 4: Add this line at the VERY BOTTOM of the file:
      auth required pam_faillock.so authfail deny=5 unlock_time=600

      What this means: Record the failed attempt after authentication fails.

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 5: Configure the faillock settings file
      sudo nano /etc/security/faillock.conf

  Step 6: Add these lines:
      # Lock after 5 failed attempts
      deny = 5

      # Automatically unlock after 600 seconds (10 minutes)
      unlock_time = 600

      # Count failures that occur within 900 seconds (15 minutes)
      fail_interval = 900

      # Write failures to audit log
      audit

      # Don't show lockout messages (security through obscurity)
      silent

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 7: Backup common-password before making changes
      sudo cp /etc/pam.d/common-password /etc/pam.d/common-password.bak

  Step 8: Open the common-password PAM file
      sudo nano /etc/pam.d/common-password

  Step 9: Add this line at the TOP of the file:
      password requisite pam_pwquality.so retry=3

      What this means: Enforce password quality rules. Allow 3 retries
      if the password is too weak before failing.

  Step 10: Find the line containing pam_unix.so and add 'remember=5' at the end
      Example — find this type of line:
          password [success=1 default=ignore] pam_unix.so obscure sha512
      Change it to:
          password [success=1 default=ignore] pam_unix.so obscure sha512 remember=5

      The 'remember=5' setting stores the last 5 password hashes and prevents
      reuse of any of the last 5 passwords.

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 11: Remove 'nullok' from all PAM files
      grep -rl "nullok" /etc/pam.d/ | xargs sudo sed -i 's/nullok//g'

      What this does: 'nullok' allows login with an empty (null) password.
      Removing it means users MUST have a password set to log in.

HOW TO VERIFY:
      grep "pam_faillock" /etc/pam.d/common-auth
  Should show two lines — one with preauth, one with authfail.

      grep "pam_pwquality" /etc/pam.d/common-password
  Should show the pwquality line.

  Test lockout: Try logging in with a wrong password 5 times.
  The account should be locked. Check with:
      sudo faillock --user <username>


================================================================================
SECTION 9 - PASSWORD AGING & INACTIVE ACCOUNT LOCK
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  Password aging enforces that passwords are changed periodically.
  Inactive account locking disables accounts that have not been used
  for a defined period after their password expires.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Passwords can be compromised without the user knowing. Regular password
  changes limit the window an attacker can use a stolen credential.
  Inactive accounts (e.g. former employees, service accounts no longer in use)
  are a common attack vector — locking them automatically reduces this risk.

  Settings:
  - PASS_MAX_DAYS 90: Password must be changed every 90 days
  - PASS_MIN_DAYS 7: Password cannot be changed again for 7 days
    (prevents users from changing password 5 times quickly to reuse old one)
  - PASS_WARN_AGE 14: Warn user 14 days before password expires
  - Inactive lock: Lock account 30 days after password expires

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Open the login defaults file
      sudo nano /etc/login.defs

  Step 2: Find and update these three lines (or add them if missing):
      PASS_MAX_DAYS   90
      PASS_MIN_DAYS   7
      PASS_WARN_AGE   14

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 3: Set accounts to lock 30 days after password expiry
      sudo useradd -D -f 30

      This sets the default for all NEW accounts. For existing accounts,
      you must apply it manually in the next steps.

  Step 4: List all regular (non-system) user accounts
      awk -F: '($3 >= 1000 && $1 != "nobody") {print $1}' /etc/passwd

      Write down all the usernames shown.

  Step 5: Apply password aging to EACH username found in Step 4
      sudo chage --maxdays 90 --mindays 7 --warndays 14 <username>

      Replace <username> with each actual username. Repeat for all users.

  Step 6: Verify the aging settings for each user
      sudo chage -l <username>

      Look for:
      - Maximum number of days between password change: 90
      - Minimum number of days between password change: 7
      - Number of days of warning before password expires: 14

HOW TO VERIFY:
      grep "^PASS_" /etc/login.defs
  Should show your three settings.

      sudo chage -l <username>
  Should show the aging settings are applied.


================================================================================
SECTION 10 - UMASK & SESSION TIMEOUT
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  umask (user file creation mask) controls the default permissions assigned
  to newly created files and directories. A umask of 027 means new files
  get permissions 640 (owner read/write, group read, others nothing) and
  new directories get 750 (owner all, group read/execute, others nothing).

  TMOUT is a shell variable that automatically logs out an idle session
  after a specified number of seconds.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Without proper umask, users may create files that are world-readable by
  default, accidentally exposing sensitive data to other users on the system.

  Without session timeout, an unattended terminal (e.g. admin walks away
  from their desk) remains open indefinitely. An attacker with physical or
  remote access to that session gets full admin access without needing
  a password.

HOW TO FIX - UMASK:

  Step 1: Set umask for the root account
      sudo nano /root/.bash_profile
      Add this line at the bottom: umask 027
      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 2: Set umask system-wide for all users
      sudo nano /etc/profile
      Add this line at the bottom: umask 027
      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 3: Set umask in the bash configuration file
      sudo nano /etc/bash.bashrc
      Add this line at the bottom: umask 027
      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

HOW TO FIX - SESSION TIMEOUT:

  Step 4: Create a timeout script in profile.d
      (Files in /etc/profile.d/ are automatically sourced for all users)
      sudo nano /etc/profile.d/99-timeout.sh

  Step 5: Add the following three lines:
      TMOUT=900
      readonly TMOUT
      export TMOUT

      What this means:
      - TMOUT=900: Log out after 900 seconds (15 minutes) of inactivity
      - readonly TMOUT: Prevent users from changing the timeout value
      - export TMOUT: Make the setting apply to all child processes

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 6: Set correct permissions on the script
      sudo chmod 644 /etc/profile.d/99-timeout.sh

HOW TO VERIFY:
      source /etc/profile.d/99-timeout.sh && echo $TMOUT
  Should output: 900

      umask
  Should output: 0027

  To test timeout: Open a new terminal, log in, and leave it idle for
  15 minutes — the session should close automatically.


================================================================================
SECTION 11 - CRON & AT HARDENING
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  cron is the standard Linux job scheduler — it runs commands automatically
  at specified times. 'at' is similar but runs a command once at a future time.
  By default, any user can schedule cron jobs.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  If any user can schedule cron jobs, a malicious user or compromised account
  can use cron to schedule persistent backdoors or run malicious code at
  privileged times. By using cron.allow, we create a whitelist — only users
  listed in the file can use cron. Using at.allow does the same for 'at'.
  Removing the .deny files is also important because if both exist,
  .allow takes precedence but having both is confusing and risky.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Remove the deny files (we will use allow files instead)
      sudo rm -f /etc/cron.deny
      sudo rm -f /etc/at.deny

  Step 2: Create the allow files
      sudo touch /etc/cron.allow
      sudo touch /etc/at.allow

  Step 3: Allow only root to use cron and at
      echo "root" | sudo tee /etc/cron.allow
      echo "root" | sudo tee /etc/at.allow

      Note: Add other authorized usernames on separate lines if needed.

  Step 4: Set ownership and permissions
      sudo chown root:root /etc/cron.allow /etc/at.allow
      sudo chmod 600 /etc/cron.allow /etc/at.allow

  Step 5: Secure the main crontab file
      sudo chown root:root /etc/crontab
      sudo chmod 600 /etc/crontab

  Step 6: Secure all cron directories
      sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.hourly
      sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.daily
      sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.weekly
      sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.monthly
      sudo chmod 700 /etc/cron.d

HOW TO VERIFY:
      cat /etc/cron.allow
  Should show: root

      ls -la /etc/cron.allow
  Should show: -rw------- root root

      ls /etc/cron.deny 2>/dev/null || echo "cron.deny removed - GOOD"
  Should say "cron.deny removed - GOOD"


================================================================================
SECTION 12 - FILE & DIRECTORY PERMISSIONS
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  Certain critical system files must have specific ownership and permissions.
  These files control user accounts, passwords, and system configuration.
  If they have incorrect permissions, unauthorized users could read or
  modify them.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  /etc/shadow contains hashed passwords. If it is world-readable, an attacker
  can copy the hashes and crack them offline. If GRUB config is not protected,
  an attacker with physical access can bypass security by editing boot parameters.
  Home directories should not be readable by other users — they may contain
  SSH keys, browser data, scripts, or sensitive files.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Secure /etc/passwd (user account info — readable but not writable)
      sudo chown root:root /etc/passwd
      sudo chmod 644 /etc/passwd

  Step 2: Secure /etc/shadow (password hashes — only root and shadow group)
      sudo chown root:shadow /etc/shadow
      sudo chmod 640 /etc/shadow

  Step 3: Secure /etc/group (group info — readable but not writable)
      sudo chown root:root /etc/group
      sudo chmod 644 /etc/group

  Step 4: Secure /etc/gshadow (group passwords — only root and shadow group)
      sudo chown root:shadow /etc/gshadow
      sudo chmod 640 /etc/gshadow

  Step 5: Secure GRUB bootloader config
      sudo chown root:root /boot/grub/grub.cfg
      sudo chmod 400 /boot/grub/grub.cfg

      chmod 400 means only root can read it, nobody can write or execute.

  Step 6: Set home directories to 750 (owner full, group read/execute, others nothing)
      awk -F: '($3 >= 1000 && $7 != "/usr/sbin/nologin") {print $6}' /etc/passwd | \
      xargs sudo chmod 750

  Step 7: Find accounts with no password set
      sudo awk -F: '($2 == "" || $2 == "!") {print $1}' /etc/shadow

  Step 8: Lock any account found without a password
      sudo passwd -l <username>

      The -l flag locks the account so it cannot be used for login.

HOW TO VERIFY:
      ls -la /etc/shadow
  Should show: -rw-r----- root shadow

      ls -la /etc/passwd
  Should show: -rw-r--r-- root root

      ls -la /boot/grub/grub.cfg
  Should show: -r-------- root root


================================================================================
SECTION 13 - NTP / TIME SYNCHRONIZATION
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  NTP (Network Time Protocol) keeps the system clock synchronized with
  accurate internet time servers. Chrony is the recommended NTP client
  for Ubuntu 24.04 — it is faster to synchronize and more accurate than
  the older ntpd daemon.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Accurate time is critical for:
  - Security logs: If the clock is wrong, log timestamps are unreliable
    and it becomes impossible to correlate events across systems.
  - SSL/TLS certificates: Certificates have validity periods. A wrong clock
    can cause certificate validation failures.
  - Kerberos authentication: Kerberos requires clocks to be within 5 minutes
    of each other or authentication fails.
  - Audit trails: Forensic investigations rely on accurate timestamps.
  CIS requires that a single time synchronization service is running and
  that it is properly configured.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Install chrony
      sudo apt install chrony -y

  Step 2: Enable chrony to start at boot
      sudo systemctl enable chrony

  Step 3: Start chrony now
      sudo systemctl start chrony

  Step 4: Edit chrony configuration
      sudo nano /etc/chrony/chrony.conf

  Step 5: Ensure the following lines are present:
      # Use Ubuntu's NTP pool (adjust to your organization's NTP server if required)
      pool 2.ubuntu.pool.ntp.org iburst

      # Allow chrony to make a large step adjustment at startup
      makestep 1 3

      # Sync the hardware clock (RTC) to the system clock
      rtcsync

      # Reject time updates that are too large (sanity check)
      maxupdateskew 100.0

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 6: Restart chrony to apply new config
      sudo systemctl restart chrony

HOW TO VERIFY:
      chronyc tracking

  Look for:
  - "System time" offset should be very small (less than 1 second)
  - "Leap status" should be "Normal"

      systemctl is-active chrony
  Should output: active


================================================================================
SECTION 14 - SUDO HARDENING
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  sudo allows authorized users to run commands as root (or another user).
  The sudoers file controls who can use sudo and what they can run.
  We add logging, PTY requirement, and remove NOPASSWD entries.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Without sudo logging, there is no audit trail of who ran what as root.
  The 'use_pty' requirement prevents attackers from using sudo in scripts
  that run in the background (non-interactively) — a common technique for
  privilege escalation. NOPASSWD entries in sudoers allow users to run
  commands as root without providing their password — a serious risk if
  the account is compromised.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Ensure sudo is installed
      sudo apt install sudo -y

  Step 2: Create a CIS-specific sudoers drop-in file
      sudo nano /etc/sudoers.d/99-cis

  Step 3: Add the following lines:
      # Log all sudo commands to a dedicated log file
      Defaults logfile=/var/log/sudo.log

      # Require a real terminal (PTY) to use sudo
      # This blocks background/non-interactive sudo abuse
      Defaults use_pty

      # Don't show the password as asterisks (don't even hint a password is typed)
      Defaults !visiblepw

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 4: Set correct permissions on the sudoers file
      sudo chmod 440 /etc/sudoers.d/99-cis

  Step 5: Validate the sudoers configuration
      sudo visudo -c
      Must output: "/etc/sudoers: parsed OK" — if not, fix errors before proceeding.

  Step 6: Check for NOPASSWD entries (these are dangerous — review and remove)
      grep -r 'NOPASSWD' /etc/sudoers /etc/sudoers.d/

      If any NOPASSWD entries appear, edit the relevant file and remove
      the NOPASSWD keyword, requiring a password for those commands.

HOW TO VERIFY:
      sudo visudo -c
  Should output: parsed OK

      cat /var/log/sudo.log
  Should show your sudo commands being logged after any sudo use.


================================================================================
SECTION 15 - AUDITD (System Auditing)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  auditd is the Linux audit daemon. It records security-relevant events
  on the system — who changed which files, who ran privileged commands,
  failed access attempts, and system configuration changes. Audit rules
  define which events to record.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Without auditd, if a system is compromised, there may be no record of
  what the attacker did. With auditd properly configured:
  - You can detect unauthorized changes to critical files
  - You have a forensic trail for incident investigation
  - You can detect privilege escalation attempts
  - You meet compliance requirements for log integrity
  CIS requires specific audit rules covering time changes, user modifications,
  login events, permission changes, and privileged command use.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Install audit daemon and plugins
      sudo apt install auditd audispd-plugins -y

  Step 2: Enable and start auditd
      sudo systemctl enable auditd
      sudo systemctl start auditd

  Step 3: Create CIS audit rules file
      sudo nano /etc/audit/rules.d/99-cis.rules

  Step 4: Add the following audit rules:

      # Audit system time changes (detects clock manipulation)
      -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S adjtimex -S settimeofday -k time-change
      -a always,exit -F arch=b32 -S adjtimex -S settimeofday -S stime -k time-change
      -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S clock_settime -k time-change
      -w /etc/localtime -p wa -k time-change

      # Audit user and group account changes
      -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity
      -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity
      -w /etc/gshadow -p wa -k identity
      -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity

      # Audit network configuration changes
      -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S sethostname -S setdomainname -k system-locale
      -w /etc/issue -p wa -k system-locale
      -w /etc/issue.net -p wa -k system-locale
      -w /etc/hosts -p wa -k system-locale

      # Audit AppArmor policy changes
      -w /etc/apparmor/ -p wa -k MAC-policy
      -w /etc/apparmor.d/ -p wa -k MAC-policy

      # Audit login and logout events
      -w /var/log/faillog -p wa -k logins
      -w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins

      # Audit active session tracking
      -w /var/run/utmp -p wa -k session
      -w /var/log/wtmp -p wa -k logins
      -w /var/log/btmp -p wa -k logins

      # Audit permission and ownership changes
      -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod -S fchmod -S fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=4294967295 -k perm_mod
      -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown -S fchown -S fchownat -S lchown -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=4294967295 -k perm_mod

      # Audit unauthorized access attempts
      -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S creat -S open -S openat -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -k access
      -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S creat -S open -S openat -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -k access

      # Audit privileged command use (sudo, su)
      -a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/sudo -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -k privileged
      -a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/su -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -k privileged

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 5: Load the new rules
      sudo augenrules --load

  Step 6: Restart auditd
      sudo systemctl restart auditd

HOW TO VERIFY:
      sudo auditctl -l
  Should list all your configured rules.

      sudo systemctl is-active auditd
  Should output: active

      sudo ausearch -k time-change
  After making a time-related change, this should show audit events.


================================================================================
SECTION 16 - LOGGING (rsyslog & journald)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  rsyslog is the standard system logging daemon. It collects log messages
  from the kernel, services, and applications and writes them to log files.
  journald is systemd's journal service — it captures boot messages and
  service logs. Configuring both ensures comprehensive logging.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Log files are essential for detecting attacks, investigating incidents,
  and meeting compliance requirements. If logs are not persistent, they
  are lost on reboot. If log file permissions are too open, attackers can
  read logs (learning about the environment) or modify them to cover tracks.
  CIS requires:
  - Logs must be persistent (survive reboot)
  - Log files should be mode 640 (owner read/write, group read, others nothing)
  - Logs should be forwarded from journald to syslog

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Install rsyslog
      sudo apt install rsyslog -y

  Step 2: Enable and start rsyslog
      sudo systemctl enable rsyslog
      sudo systemctl start rsyslog

  Step 3: Open rsyslog configuration
      sudo nano /etc/rsyslog.conf

  Step 4: Add this line to restrict log file permissions
      $FileCreateMode 0640

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 5: Restart rsyslog
      sudo systemctl restart rsyslog

  Step 6: Open journald configuration
      sudo nano /etc/systemd/journald.conf

  Step 7: Under the [Journal] section, set these values:
      Storage=persistent
      (Saves logs to /var/log/journal — survives reboots)

      Compress=yes
      (Compresses old journal files to save space)

      ForwardToSyslog=yes
      (Sends journal entries to rsyslog as well)

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 8: Restart journald
      sudo systemctl restart systemd-journald

HOW TO VERIFY:
      ls -la /var/log/syslog
  Should show permissions -rw-r----- (640)

      ls /var/log/journal/
  Should show a directory with journal files (persistent storage enabled)

      systemctl is-active rsyslog
  Should output: active


================================================================================
SECTION 17 - AIDE (File Integrity Monitoring)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  AIDE (Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment) is a file integrity
  monitoring tool. It creates a database snapshot of critical system files
  (recording file sizes, permissions, checksums, timestamps) and can then
  compare the current state of files against that snapshot to detect changes.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  A sophisticated attacker who gains access to a system will often modify
  system files — replacing binaries with trojaned versions, adding backdoor
  scripts, or modifying configuration files. AIDE detects these changes by
  comparing file checksums against the known-good baseline.
  Running AIDE daily means you get alerted within 24 hours of any unauthorized
  change to critical system files. This is a key detective control.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Install AIDE and its common configuration
      sudo apt install aide aide-common -y

  Step 2: Initialize the AIDE database
      sudo aideinit -y -f

      This scans the entire system and builds the baseline database.
      It takes several minutes — this is normal. Wait for it to complete.

  Step 3: Copy the new database to the active database location
      sudo cp /var/lib/aide/aide.db.new /var/lib/aide/aide.db

  Step 4: Create a daily automated check script
      sudo nano /etc/cron.daily/aide-check

  Step 5: Add the following content:
      #!/bin/bash
      /usr/bin/aide --check >> /var/log/aide-check.log 2>&1

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 6: Make the script executable
      sudo chmod 755 /etc/cron.daily/aide-check

  Step 7: Run AIDE manually to confirm it works
      sudo aide --check

      On first run after initialization, it should report no changes.
      After making legitimate changes to the system, you must update
      the database with: sudo aide --update

HOW TO VERIFY:
      sudo aide --check
  First run should show "no differences found" or similar.

      ls -la /var/lib/aide/aide.db
  Database file should exist.

      ls /etc/cron.daily/aide-check
  Script should be present.


================================================================================
SECTION 18 - SYSCTL (Network & Kernel Hardening)
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  sysctl is used to read and modify kernel parameters at runtime.
  These parameters control how the kernel handles network traffic,
  memory, and security features. The settings are stored in files
  under /etc/sysctl.d/ and are applied at boot.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Default kernel settings are often configured for compatibility, not security.
  For example:
  - ip_forward=1 would allow the server to route traffic between networks
    (not needed on a regular server — could allow traffic tunneling attacks)
  - accept_redirects=1 allows ICMP redirects, which can be used to redirect
    traffic through an attacker's system (man-in-the-middle attack)
  - randomize_va_space=0 disables ASLR (Address Space Layout Randomization)
    making memory exploitation much easier for attackers
  These hardened sysctl settings close many common network attack vectors.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Create a CIS sysctl configuration file
      sudo nano /etc/sysctl.d/99-cis.conf

  Step 2: Add ALL of the following settings:

      # NETWORK SECURITY

      # Disable IP packet forwarding (server should not route traffic)
      net.ipv4.ip_forward = 0

      # Disable sending ICMP redirects (prevent routing table poisoning)
      net.ipv4.conf.all.send_redirects = 0
      net.ipv4.conf.default.send_redirects = 0

      # Disable source routing (attacker-specified packet routes)
      net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_source_route = 0
      net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_source_route = 0

      # Disable ICMP redirect acceptance (prevent MITM via routing changes)
      net.ipv4.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0
      net.ipv4.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0
      net.ipv4.conf.all.secure_redirects = 0
      net.ipv4.conf.default.secure_redirects = 0

      # Log suspicious packets that should not exist (martians)
      net.ipv4.conf.all.log_martians = 1
      net.ipv4.conf.default.log_martians = 1

      # Ignore broadcast pings (Smurf attack prevention)
      net.ipv4.icmp_echo_ignore_broadcasts = 1

      # Ignore bogus ICMP error responses
      net.ipv4.icmp_ignore_bogus_error_responses = 1

      # Enable reverse path filtering (anti-spoofing)
      net.ipv4.conf.all.rp_filter = 1
      net.ipv4.conf.default.rp_filter = 1

      # Enable TCP SYN cookies (SYN flood attack protection)
      net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies = 1

      # Disable IPv6 router advertisements (prevent rogue router attacks)
      net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_ra = 0
      net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_ra = 0

      # Disable IPv6 ICMP redirects
      net.ipv6.conf.all.accept_redirects = 0
      net.ipv6.conf.default.accept_redirects = 0

      # KERNEL SECURITY

      # Full ASLR - randomize memory addresses (makes exploits much harder)
      kernel.randomize_va_space = 2

      # Restrict access to kernel log (dmesg) to root only
      kernel.dmesg_restrict = 1

      # Disable core dumps from SUID programs (prevent data leakage)
      fs.suid_dumpable = 0

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 3: Apply all settings immediately (without rebooting)
      sudo sysctl --system

HOW TO VERIFY:
      sudo sysctl net.ipv4.ip_forward
  Expected: net.ipv4.ip_forward = 0

      sudo sysctl kernel.randomize_va_space
  Expected: kernel.randomize_va_space = 2

      sudo sysctl net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies
  Expected: net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies = 1


================================================================================
SECTION 19 - DISABLE UNUSED SERVICES
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  Linux systems often have many services installed and running by default
  that are not actually needed for the server's purpose. Each running
  service is a potential attack target.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  Every running service:
  - Listens on a network port (another entry point for attackers)
  - Has potential vulnerabilities that need patching
  - Consumes system resources
  - Increases the attack surface of the system

  The security principle of "least privilege" and "minimal footprint" says
  a system should run ONLY the services it actually needs. A web server does
  not need a print server (CUPS) or a mail server. A database server does
  not need a file sharing service (Samba).

  [!] IMPORTANT: Only disable services that are truly not needed.
      Disabling a required service will break functionality.
      Review each one before disabling.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Disable Avahi daemon (mDNS/DNS-SD — used for device discovery)
      sudo systemctl disable avahi-daemon
      sudo systemctl stop avahi-daemon
      (Safe to disable on most servers — needed only for local device discovery)

  Step 2: Disable CUPS (Common Unix Printing System — print spooler)
      sudo systemctl disable cups
      sudo systemctl stop cups
      (Servers do not need a print service)

  Step 3: Disable DHCP server (if this server does not assign IP addresses)
      sudo systemctl disable isc-dhcp-server
      sudo systemctl stop isc-dhcp-server

  Step 4: Disable NFS server (if not sharing files via NFS)
      sudo systemctl disable nfs-server
      sudo systemctl stop nfs-server

  Step 5: Disable RPC bind (required only for NFS and NIS)
      sudo systemctl disable rpcbind
      sudo systemctl stop rpcbind

  Step 6: Disable FTP server (use SFTP via SSH instead)
      sudo systemctl disable vsftpd
      sudo systemctl stop vsftpd

  Step 7: Disable Samba (if not sharing files with Windows systems)
      sudo systemctl disable smbd
      sudo systemctl stop smbd

  Step 8: Disable Squid proxy (if not running a proxy)
      sudo systemctl disable squid
      sudo systemctl stop squid

  Step 9: Remove insecure legacy remote access tools
      sudo apt purge telnet rsh-client talk -y

      Telnet sends data including passwords in plaintext.
      rsh (remote shell) has no encryption at all.
      Both should be replaced by SSH.

  Step 10: Clean up packages no longer needed
      sudo apt autoremove -y

HOW TO VERIFY:
      systemctl is-active avahi-daemon
  Should output: inactive

      which telnet 2>/dev/null || echo "telnet not installed - GOOD"
  Should say telnet not installed.


================================================================================
SECTION 20 - CORE DUMPS
================================================================================

WHAT IS THIS?
  A core dump is a file created by the operating system when a program
  crashes — it contains the complete memory state of the program at the
  time of the crash. Core dumps from SUID programs (programs that run as
  root regardless of who executes them) can contain sensitive information
  like passwords, encryption keys, or private data from memory.

WHY DOES IT MATTER?
  If a SUID program crashes and creates a core dump, that dump file could
  contain sensitive information from root's memory space. A regular user
  who can read the dump file could extract this sensitive data.
  Disabling core dumps from SUID programs prevents this data leakage.

HOW TO FIX:

  Step 1: Open the limits configuration file
      sudo nano /etc/security/limits.conf

  Step 2: Add this line at the bottom:
      * hard core 0

      What this means: For ALL users (*), set a hard limit of 0 for
      core dump size. Hard limits cannot be overridden by users.

      Save and exit: Press Ctrl+X, then Y, then Enter

  Step 3: Immediately disable SUID core dumps via sysctl
      sudo sysctl -w fs.suid_dumpable=0

  Step 4: Make the sysctl setting persistent (add to the CIS sysctl file)
      echo 'fs.suid_dumpable = 0' | sudo tee -a /etc/sysctl.d/99-cis.conf

      Note: If you already added this in Section 18, skip this step.

HOW TO VERIFY:
      sudo sysctl fs.suid_dumpable
  Expected: fs.suid_dumpable = 0

      grep "hard core" /etc/security/limits.conf
  Expected: * hard core 0


